<h4 id="background">Background</h4>
<p>Aristotle said:‚Äùthe man is rational animal.‚Äù</p>

<h4 id="species-of-argument">Species of Argument</h4>
<p>Deductive, inductive, abductive, argument by analogy,</p>

<h4 id="terminology">terminology</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Induction: using past experience to make future predictions.
    <ul>
      <li>Because aspirin can cure most people‚Äôs headache according to your expericence,
you believe it cure your headache too.</li>
      <li>Premise 1: Most men in ancient Athens had beards</li>
      <li>Premise 2: Socrates was a man who lived in ancient Athens</li>
      <li>Conclusion: Therefore, Socrates probably had a beard.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Abduction: Drawing a conclusion based on the explanation that best explains a
state of events, rather than from evidence provided by the premises.
    <ul>
      <li>Anna told you she failed her physics midterm</li>
      <li>Anna hasn‚Äôt been in physics class since you teacher graded the exams</li>
      <li>Anna has been in sociology class. which meets right after physics.</li>
      <li>Conclusion: Anna dropped physics(we can‚Äôt get this conclusion by induction or
deduction, but the conclusion can explain the event very well.)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Deduction:
    <ul>
      <li>Premise: every cat has four claws.</li>
      <li>Evidence: Tom is a cat.</li>
      <li>Conclusion: Tom has four claws.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

